If the test is stressed, more events than what will fit in a segment / batch may be emitted. Ordering isn't guaranteed across segments / batches.

I've attached the log file(s) for my macosx-aarch64 jdk-23+15 sighting:

$ unzip -l jdk-23+15_macosx-aarch64.8323196.zip
Archive: jdk-23+15_macosx-aarch64.8323196.zip

--------- ---------- ----- ----
    19553 03-23-2024 02:59 jdk-23+15_2/failures.macosx-aarch64/TestOrdered.jtr.fastdebug
--------- -------
    19553 1 file

Update: I searched for a 'recording.jfr' and none was found among the
artifacts for this fastdebug directory:

$ find build/macosx-aarch64-normal-server-fastdebug -name 'recording.jfr'
<empty output>

> What does "stress testing" mean in this case?

I have a stress kit that I use to do testing on every promoted build.
Basically I execute a bunch of test suites serially along with a number
of focused tests in parallel with release, fastdebug and slowdebug bits.
The target goal is that a run will execute for 24 hours or a little more
and the load average is driven very, very high (25 -> 100+).

The parallel stress tests are exercising thread lists, suspend/resume
and other interesting sub-systems. The serial test suites are just ones
that I typically run for subsystems I'm interested in.

So when jdk/jfr/api/consumer/filestream/TestOrdered.java executed
it was with fastdebug bits, the concurrency factor was set to 12 and
the timeout factor was set to 6. This means that the test was executed
with up to 11 other JDK tests along with the 3 parallel tests that were
executing at the time (1 each: release, fastdebug, slowdebug bits).

> Can it be located? It may help to reproduce the issue.

Since I already started stress testing for jdk-22+31, the artifacts for the
jdk-22+30 runs are gone... sorry about that. I double checked the
artifacts that I do squirrel away for failures and a 'recording.jfr' file is not
one of them...

What does "stress testing" mean in this case? The test creates a recording file:

Path p = Files.createTempFile("recording", ".jfr");
r.dump(p);

Can it be located? It may help to reproduce the issue.
